The Macedonians voted on Sunday to decide on the change of the country's name to "Republic of North Macedonia", an initiative that would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece that blocked their applications for membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which is part of a province called Macedonia, insists that the name of its neighbour north represents a complaint about its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The two governments signed an agreement in June based on the proposal for a new name, but the nationalist opponents argue that the change would be a blow to the ethnic identity of the population of Macedonia, mostly Slavic.
President Gjorge Ivanov said that he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts as to whether the voter turnout will be sufficient to meet the 50% required for the referendum to be valid.
The referendum question was as follows: "Is it in favour of NATO and EU entry with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the change of name, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to continue the efforts of membership in bodies with the EU and NATO for Macedonia, one of the countries that have emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia.
"I have come today to vote for the future of our country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live free under the auspices of the European Union, because that means a safer life for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although the referendum is not legally binding, a sufficient number of members of parliament stated that it would respect the result of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The National Election Committee stated that there had been no irregularities until one afternoon.
However, the influx was only 16%, compared to the 34% obtained in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66% of registered voters attended to vote.
"I have come to vote for my children; our place is in Europe," said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski, a voter of the capital Skopje.
The Prime Minister of Macedonia, Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko vote in the referendum on the change of the country's name, which would open the doors for membership of NATO and the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavarvarkov prepared a small stage and put chairs in front of the tents mounted by those who will boycott the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to stick headlong and not for the door of service," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want us to receive Macedonia, we can address others like China and Russia to become part of Eurasian integration."
Prime Minister Zaev said that entry into NATO will bring much-needed investments to Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of over 20%.
"I believe that the overwhelming majority will be in favour, as more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after voting.
According to him, a "yes" would be the "confirmation of our future".
A poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Political Research revealed that between 30 and 43% of voters would participate in the referendum, a value lower than the required influx.
Another poll, conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, found that 57% of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
