Unfortunately, today, it is no longer the tone of many of the meetings and the promise of "kinder and gentler" politics has been forgotten a long time ago, if it has ever come true.
It has become increasingly apparent that different views are not tolerated in the Labour Party, and that each opinion is judged whether or not it is acceptable for the leadership of the party.
This began a short time after Jeremy had taken the lead, because the colleagues with whom he thought he shared a similar political perspective began to expect me to turn around and assume positions with which he would never agree - whether they were on national security or on the EU single market.
Whenever I speak in public (and it doesn't really matter what I say), there is a stream of insults on social networks that call for "resignation," denouncing the policies of the centre, telling me that I must not belong to the Labour Party.
And it's not just me who's going through this.
In fact, I know that I am more lucky than some of my colleagues, since the comments addressed to me tend to be of a political nature.
I am amazed at the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who face a barrage of sexist or racist insults every day, but who never fall back before them.
One of the aspects that most disappoint me in this age of politics is how these levels of insult have become normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we have ceased to be inclusive, and with each motion of "censorship" or change of the selection rules the party narrows its views.
I have received numerous advices over the last two years urging me to keep my head low, not to be so expressive, and so "it would do all right" for me.
But that's not what I came to do.
Since I joined the Labour Party for 32 years as a student, impelled by the neglect of Thatcher's government that left my comprehensive school classroom literally in rubble, I have tried to fight for better public services for those who need them most, either as an autarch or as a minister in the government.
I have never hidden my policies, including in the last elections.
No one in Nottingham East could have been somewhat confused about my political positions and areas of disagreement with the current leadership.
For those who promoted the motion on Friday, all I have to say is that when the country goes to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on the subject of my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in fact, the message I have is not for the Nottingham Momentum; it is for my constituents, members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no threats of "resignation" or political records will prevent me from acting in the sense of what I believe to be the interests of all of you.
Chris Leslie is a Member in Parliament by Nottingham East
