"The sea is ours": Bolivia, a landless country, expects the court to reopen a path to the Pacific
Marines patrol a naval base covered with rope in La Paz.
Public buildings have a blue-sea flag.
The naval bases of Lake Titicaca for the Amazon bear the motto: "The sea is ours by right.
It's a duty to recover it."
Throughout Bolivia, a landlocked country, is still alive the memory of a lost coastline for Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century, as well as the desire to sail once again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps at the highest point of decades, since Bolivia awaits a sentence of the International Court of Justice on 1 October, after five years of deliberation.
"Bolivia has the impetus, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, a positive perspective on the result," said Roberto Calzadilla, Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will attend the delivery of the TIJ sentence on giant screens scattered throughout the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of the claim of their country, so that, after decades of uncertain negotiations, Chile will be forced to negotiate, granting Bolivia a sovereign way out to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic Bolivian indigenous president, who faces a controversial battle for re-election in the coming year, also has a lot at stake in Monday's sentence.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," was the president's vote last August.
However, some analysts believe it unlikely that the court would rule in favor of Bolivia, and that little would change even in the opposite case.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, has no power to assign Chilean territory to another country and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
That TIJ's sentence is delivered only six months after the hearing of the final allegations indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from promoting the Bolivian cause, the last four years may have harmed it.
"The issue of access to the sea was seized by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric undermined some residual Chilean goodwill, he suggested.
At a time in the future, Bolivia and Chile will continue the talks, but it will be extremely difficult to maintain the dialogue after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltze, Bolivian representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making process was unusually rapid.
Next Monday will give Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and a possibility of "ending 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, one of Latin America's most popular presidents, was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
" Bolivia will never dispense with its right of access to the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The sentence is an opportunity to understand that we must overcome the past."
