John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
The independent schools of Scotland benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, having this trend pursued in 2018 with another set of outstanding results in the exams, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30 000 students scattered throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to obtain the best level of service for both students and parents.
Independent schools intend to prepare their students for further study and access to universities, as well as for the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a tailored curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought-after theme in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If we talk to a man in a language he understands, we can get into his mind.
If we speak with him in his own language, we can enter into his heart."
This quote reminds us that we cannot only rely on English when we want to create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of this year's recent exams, we find that the languages are at the top of the tables, with the highest rates of use of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages reached the maximum classification of A.
These data, collected in the 74 schools under the SCIS, show that 72% of the students obtained the maximum grade of A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are favoring foreign languages as vital competences that will unquestionably serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now viewed in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and not only.
A UK Commission survey for Employment and Skills in 2014 concluded that, among the reasons for employers' difficulty in filling vacancies, 17% were concerned with a lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowing other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential job opportunities requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with a fitness for life like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person at the forefront of competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to keep a conversation, the French language being the only language spoken by a proportion of two digits, 15%.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for today's children.
The domain of several languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children with the best chances of finding employment with relevance.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a set of languages to choose from in independent schools, supported by specialized teaching staff in the area.
The independent Scottish schools are committed to providing a pedagogical environment that prepares children and gives them the necessary skills for success, whatever the future holds them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance for the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do this.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
