North Korea says "no thinking" of unilateral disarmament without trust
The Minister for Foreign Affairs of North Korea told the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions was aggravating the mistrust of the United States and that there was no way for the country to unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" last year, such as the interruption of nuclear tests and missiles, the dismantling of the nuclear test centre and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we don't see any corresponding US response," he said.
"Without confidence in the US there will be no confidence in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way to proceed with our disarmament first."
Although Ri has recycled known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in that they do not reject unilateral denuclearization outright, in contrast to the previous positions of Pyongyang.
Ri reported a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever held between a US President in exercise and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim undertook to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump provided security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the Korean war of 1950-53, but the United States claims that Pyongyang has first to abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften the harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insist on "denuclearization first" and increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its objective in a coercive manner, opposing to "the declaration of the end of war," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the prolongation of sanctions is aggravating our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been reported by the US leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the last five months, adding: "If the interested party in this matter were South Korea and not the USA, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year's, when he told the UN General Assembly that directing North Korea's rockets towards US territory was inevitable after Mr. Mau Trump called Kim the "man of rockets" on a suicide mission.
Last year at the United Nations, Trump, who had threatened to "destroy completely" North Korea, filled Kim with praise for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said that much was still to be done and that sanctions would have to go on until the denuclearization of North Korea.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn't have a calendar for it, saying that "it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo declared to the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The implementation of the sanctions of the Security Council must continue vigorously until the denuclearisation is complete, final and verifiable."
The Security Council unanimously strengthened the sanctions against North Korea imposed since 2006 in an attempt to strangle the financing of North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompey met with Ri at the margins of the UN General Assembly and declared after he would visit Pyongyang again in the month coming to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit didn't go well.
Pyongyang left in July saying that progress had been made, although after North Korea denounced him for "making demands of gangsters.
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea committed to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States "take corresponding action".
Pompeo said that Kim had told him that the "relevant measures" they were looking for were the security guarantees provided by Trump in Singapore, as well as initiatives to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend courses that teach them how to rest enough
A new course at Harvard University this year put all of its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat machasta culture to study in caffeine-impregnated "directs".
One professor concluded that the students of this university at the top of the world ranking often did not have the slightest idea about the most basic concepts about the care they should have with themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, who believes he is the first of his kind in the United States.
The inspiration for the course arose after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why are you just telling me this in the last year of the course?"
The young woman said no one had ever mentioned the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university health services, said that the institution decided to introduce the course after having concluded that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In a section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, slippers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to pick up the bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risk of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know it won't change students' behavior instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, as we all have the right to know the health effects of smoking option," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "directing" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students make this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we sleep enough and with quality should be a "secret weapon" of the students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid fattening, because the deprivation of sleep puts the brain in the way of hunger, making them constantly starved.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler conceive of the course after attending one of his classes last year at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a course for the entire campus, he said.
The next step, according to their expectations, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar study program before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider using an alarm to go to bed, as well as to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can deregulate the circadian rhythm and lead to problems in falling asleep.
