Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, created a startup that aims to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of this legendary technology character, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee's open source code platform, Solid.
It allows users to decide where their data is stored and who has access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokingly stated that the underlying intention of Inrupt is to "dominating the world".
"We have to do it now," he said about the startup.
"It's an historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own "on-line personal storage", or POD.
This may contain contact lists, task lists, calendars, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available in one browser and at the same time.
What is unique about the personal storage of online data is that it is up to the user to decide who has access to what type of information.
The company calls it "personal capacity through data".
The idea of Inrupt, according to the CEO of John Bruce, is to provide adequate resources, processes and skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some internal programmers hired to work on the project and a community of volunteering programmers.
Beginning this week, world-wide technology creators will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about the introduction or not of a total change in which all their business models are turned from avian from one day to the next.
"We're not asking for permission."
In a publication at Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to create commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new Web created with Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on the neutrality of the Internet.
