National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New investigations are being carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands in order to reveal how bats use the landscape to search for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behavior of these singular flying mammals and to help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and fruit, as well as long-eared chestnuts and Daubenton bats in the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations scattered by the property to follow the activities of bats along the station.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and volunteers with portable detectors.
Analysis by specialists of all recordings will evaluate the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviour on a territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, advisor to the conservation of the NTS nature, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works that affect dormitories and make habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning also pose a threat, together with fly-kills and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than eyes when it comes to catching the prey.
They use a sophisticated echo location technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts who regularly carry out studies, inspections in dormitories and sometimes rescues.
He also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats, at Threave property in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scotch bats.
The property manager, David Thompson, says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threat we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many old trees and all this good habitat.
However, there's still a lot about bats that we don't know, so the work we've developed here and in the other properties will help us learn more about what they need to flourish."
It was stressed by him that it was important to check whether bats are present before maintaining the properties, since the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dormitories can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
The bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dorms.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate in helping.
It was by her saying, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we just don't know how their populations are taking revenge."
